english:
  title: Record of the Sunlit Pavilion
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Lord of Guseong, Minister Kim, once served the Tianli Emperor, studying in the Guzhang Pavilion. At that time, the esteemed Ge Wen'an of Yujiang held the post of lecturer, and Minister Kim attended upon him with the utmost reverence of a disciple. He would visit his dwelling to inquire into the profound meanings of the classics, and thereby came to master the histories and the art of poetry.

    Later, when the Zhizheng Emperor ascended, he honored Minister Kim with great courtesy and advanced him repeatedly, until he reached the rank of Grand Minister, a position near the throne itself. Though he dwelt among those draped in silk and rich with sumptuous fare, he cast off such ostentation and delighted instead in the company of refined scholars. On fair days and in beautiful seasons, they would gather to compose and sing, answering one another in verse, nurturing their spirits. Thus did he drink deeply from the wellspring of poetry's delight.

    During his hours of court duty, his thoughts often turned to his parents. When he petitioned the Emperor for leave, the sovereign graciously granted it, sending swift horses to carry him home—this occurred two or three times. At the Diamond Mountain, after offering prayers for the Emperor's longevity, he would raise wine to toast his parents in the hall, and they would rejoice. The harmony that filled his household became a matter of common praise, spoken of even now as witness to his refinement and elegant leisure.

    Many great scholars of the previous generation followed his company, including our ancestor Master Gajung. In matters of loyalty and righteous conduct, in the great principles of integrity, he did not lightly bend to the fashions of the age. When the Xuanling Emperor faced hardship in the year of the Ox, Minister Kim stood firm in his convictions, unchanging—truly surpassing the common run of men, worthy indeed to be called a gentleman. Thus did the Xuanling Emperor cherish and honor him, and from this we know how deeply his study of books had penetrated.

    Now in his dwelling in Cheonnyeong County, there are mountains to ascend and waters to contemplate. With staff and sandals, he walks back and forth—a solitude difficult to attain. In those moments when he chants with wind and moon, and playfully mocks the heavens and earth, all the former splendor and tumult, all the glittering throng of important persons and their elaborate courtesies, fade away like morning mist, growing dim as dreams, leaving not the slightest trace. Even the solitary joy of old Wusu could not surpass this.

    The Odes speak of "the gentleman's serene contentment," meaning one who dwells obscurely in humble station. Yet Minister Kim dwells hidden in mountains green and waters clear—different in circumstance, yet the same in spirit. When the Eastern Pavilion recently returned to court, he would speak of Minister Kim without ceasing, and requested that I write this record. Since Minister Kim is a senior whom I respect, I cannot refuse. Yet my prolonged illness has weakened my pen. I offer this simple reflection in response.

    Yang is the gentleman; yin is the small man. All sixty-four hexagrams of the Book of Changes uphold the yang and restrain the yin—such is how the Way of the gentleman flourishes. This is the great teaching the sages left to the world. Thus do they suppress the small man's way most profoundly. Delight and joy belong to yang; sorrow and bitterness to yin. Speaking from my own experience: after recovering from illness, I rise late and rest in the warm sun beneath the eaves. My body eases, my breath flows free, my spirit clears, my will grows firm. The joy of this—no words can measure it. Indeed, I have tested this against the ancient saying of one offering himself to his lord, and found it rings true. How much more so when icy winds blow even in summer across the northern reaches—does not Minister Kim's heart, devoted to serving his sovereign, know no rest?

    Alas, my own hair has turned half white. What then of him? I ask your forbearance with this humble offering in answer. The Eastern Pavilion replied, "It suffices. Let it be so." Thus I have set down these words as a record.
  footnotes:
    - 'Guzhang Pavilion (Guzhang Ge): The imperial library established during the Yuan Dynasty, known for its collection of important texts and manuscripts.'
    - 'The Xuanling Emperor''s hardship in the year of the Ox: Likely refers to a political crisis during the Yuan Dynasty when loyal officials like Minister Kim chose moral principle over political expediency.'
    - 'Diamond Mountain (Geumgang-san): A sacred mountain in Korea, traditionally associated with Buddhist pilgrimage and spiritual devotion.'
    - The allusion to 'old Wusu's solitary joy' references a figure known for finding contentment in humble, retired circumstances.
    - The reference to summer snows in the northern reaches evokes the hardships of distant frontier regions, used metaphorically to suggest the constancy of the virtuous minister's loyalty.
